From:	Jared Isaacman
Sent:	Sunday, November 6, 2016 9:39 PM
To:	Randy Taylor
Subject:	Intro

Randy,

It was good catching up last week. As you know, we take pride in execution at Shift4 and in that spirit, I wanted to
waste no time acting on some action items from our meeting. I have a lot of respect for what you and your
team are doing at Card Connect, so it came natural.

First, do you have any problem acting on my request to introduce me to Dave Abrams at Golden
Nugget/Landry’s? I’ll follow up with your contact with a slightly more formal request he can use to intro, but
if there are any reservations definitely let me know.

Second, I was watching CBS This Morning on Saturday (the segment is online) and it was covering all the
cyber security attacks associated with the mid-term elections. As you know, Shift4 is pretty unique in that we
are really the only payment gateway in the country (that I an-i aware of) to be listed as a validated P2PE
solution provider while also maintaining integrations to nearly all of the largest POSI PMS platforms. This
eliminates a lot of the complexity merchants (and integrated solutions) were burdened with when combining a
tokenization strategy with P2PE, which contributed to slow adoption. I thought this seemed rather relevant
to Card Connect as it should enable you to win a considerable amount of new business as you continue to
pursue that multi-billion dollar ‘enterprise’ market, free of legacy player concerns, while also making life
easier on some of your other integrated solutions.

I’d have to go back and check, but I believe the ‘all-in’ cost to Card Connect (blended between all per-auth, per-
month license and support) would be around $0.04 per transaction and should be able to be implemented very
quickly... which would make the payback (again, just on new business won) pretty attractive. I’ve always felt
that by doing this, it would also allow Card Connect to ‘bury the competition’ as any other gateway a merchant
would consider adding would essentially amount to a second, redundant P2PE validated solution against a
single point of failure.

Would you be interested in discussing? I know there is sensitivity at FDC/BAMS around anything that might
upset the First Data Rapid Connect platform, but this should only result in additional revenue by reducing the
PCI burden on some big merchants which would seemingly justify it.

Thanks,
Jared

Subject:	CardConnect and Shift4 - RE: Intro

Randy,

Circling back to my prior email regarding CardConnect and the opportunity for Shift4's validated P2PE
solution...

I reviewed our notes and noticed that CardConnect was once a reseller of Shift4 services (pre-IPO) but that
relationship has since ended. We should probably revisit this for a few reasons.

As you are likely aware, we have merchants live today running a number of the largest POS/PMS applications
with a P2PE + Tokenization strategy. This includes Oracle Micros (3700, 9700, Simphony 1&2, and hosted
products), Agilisys (various), and many others. We are also working with all the players you would expect in
hospitality and have several national brands making a lot of noise about their P2PE deployments with us. I can
share their names if we have a mutual NDA in place (I thought we did, but it will take me a few days to go
back and check).

As such, I wanted to make a request that will cost CardConnect considerably less than pursuing this strategy
alone ... and be far more rewarding. That request is for a 'friendly meeting'. You can invite whomever you
deem necessary to attend and we will do the same on our side.

I would like to accomplish a few objectives from the meeting (including the ability to meet many of your team
members). The first is to get a better understanding of the CardConnect strategy for P2PE. We can share all
the challenges that accompany 'doing it yourself which no one else has been able to accomplish (outside of
Shift4) and will likely take 2+ years before generating a justifiable return. We can share customer testimonials
and references in those discussions as well. We can also share the technical innovations we have employed to
support P2PE + Tokens... which I believe you will find will be valuable in achieving many CardConnect
objectives.

Second, at a high level, we can begin to discuss what a partnership would look like should CardConnect
choose to leverage our validated P2PE solution. I can price the solution, provide support expectations, and
discuss any other concerns that may arise in the meeting.

Third, understand how Shift4 can support any of the other initiatives you have underway as it relates to
enterprise accounts, your gateway strategy, or tokenization.

I'm assuming this meeting would occur at your headquarters, so can certainly make those accommodations.
I'm very flexible next week (although in Denver on Monday) and the week of the 28th. Just let me know and
thanks again for your time.

Jared
